# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: on-call-practices
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] From their conception, large chemical, refining, power generation, and other processing plants required the use of a control system to keep the process operating successfully and producing products.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Due to the fragility of the components as compared to the process, these control systems often required a control room to protect them from the elements and process conditions.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] In the early days of control rooms, they used what were referred to as "panel boards" which were loaded with control instruments and indicators.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] These were tied to sensors located in the process streams and on the outside of process equipment.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The sensors relayed their information to the control instruments via analogue signals, such as a 4-20 mA current loop in the form of twisted pair wiring.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] At first these systems merely yielded information, and a well-trained operator was required to make adjustments either by changing flow rates, or altering energy inputs to keep the process within its designed limits.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Alarms were added to alert the operator to a condition that was about to exceed a design limit, or had already exceeded a design limit.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Additionally, shutdown systems were employed to halt a process that was in danger of exceeding either safety, environmental or monetarily acceptable process limits.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Alarm were indicated to the operator by annunciator horns, and lights of different colours.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] (For instance, green lights meant OK, Yellow meant not OK, and Red meant BAD.) Panel boards were usually laid out in a manner that replicated the process flow in the plant.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] So instrumentation indicating operating units with the plant was grouped together for recognition sake and ease of problem solution.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] It was a simple matter to look at the entire panel board, and discern whether any section of the plant was running poorly.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] This was due to both the design of the instruments and the implementation of the alarms associated with the instruments.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Instrumentation companies put a lot of effort into the design and individual layout of the instruments they manufactured.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] To do this they employed behavioural psychology practices which revealed how much information a human being could collect in a quick glance.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] More complex plants had more complex panel boards, and therefore often more human operators or controllers.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Thus, in the early days of panel board systems, alarms were regulated by both size and cost.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] In essence, they were limited by the amount of available board space, and the cost of running wiring, and hooking up an annunciator (horn), indicator (light) and switches to flip to acknowledge, and clear a resolved alarm.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] It was often the case that if a new alarm was needed, an old one had to be given up.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] As technology developed, the control system and control methods were tasked to continue to advance a higher degree of plant automation with each passing year.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Highly complex material processing called for highly complex control methodologies.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Also, global competition pushed manufacturing operations to increase production while using less energy, and producing less waste.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Around the mid 80's, we entered the digital revolution.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Distributed control systems (DCS) were a boon to the industry.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The engineer could now control the process without having to understand the equipment necessary to perform the control functions.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Panel boards were no longer required, because all of the information that once came across analogue instruments could be digitised, stuffed into a computer and manipulated to achieve the same control actions once performed with amplifiers and potentiometers.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] As a side effect, that also meant that alarms were easy and cheap to configure and deploy.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] You simply typed in a location, a value to alarm on and set it to active.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The unintended result was that soon people alarmed everything.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Initial installers set an alarm at 80% and 20% of the operating range of any variable just as a habit.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The integration of programmable logic controllers, safety instrumented systems, and packaged equipment controllers has been accompanied by an overwhelming increase in associated alarms.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] One other unfortunate part of the digital revolution was that what once covered several square yards of panel space, now had to be fit into a 17-inch computer monitor.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Multiple pages of information was thus employed to replicate the information on the replaced panel board.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Alarms were used to tell an operator to go look at a page he was not viewing.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Alarms were used to tell an operator that a tank was filling.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Every mistake made in operations usually resulted in a new alarm.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] With the implementation of the OSHA 1910 regulations, HAZOPS studies usually requested several new alarms.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Incidents began to accrue as a combination of too much data collided with too little useful information.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Recognizing that alarms were becoming a problem, industrial control system users banded together and formed the Alarm Management Task Force, which was a customer advisory board led by Honeywell in 1990.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The AMTF included participants from chemical, petrochemical, and refining operations.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] They gathered and wrote a document on the issues associated with alarm management.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] This group quickly realised that alarm problems were simply a subset of a larger problem, and formed the Abnormal Situation Management Consortium (ASM is a registered trademark of Honeywell).
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium Archived 2008-09-07 at the Wayback Machine developed a research proposal and was granted funding from the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) in 1994.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The focus of this work was addressing the complex human-system interaction and factors that influence successful performance for process operators.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Automation solutions have often been developed without consideration of the human that needs to interact with the solution.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] In particular, alarms are intended to improve situation awareness for the control room operator, but a poorly configured alarm system does not achieve this goal.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium has produced documents on best practices in alarm management, as well as operator situation awareness, operator effectiveness, and other operator-oriented issues.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] These documents were originally for ASM Consortium members only, but the ASMC has recently offered these documents publicly.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The ASM consortium also participated in development of an alarm management guideline published by the Engineering Equipment & Materials Users' Association (EEMUA) in the UK.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The ASM Consortium provided data from their member companies, and contributed to the editing of the guideline.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] The result is EEMUA 191 "Alarm Systems- A Guide to Design, Management and Procurement".
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Several institutions and societies are producing standards on alarm management to assist their members in the best practices use of alarms in industrial manufacturing systems.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Among them are the ISA (ISA 18.2), API (API 1167) and NAMUR (Namur NA 102).
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Several companies also offer software packages to assist users in dealing with alarm management issues.
[src:on-call-practices/alarm-management] Among them are DCS manufacturing companies, and third-party vendors who offer add-on systems.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Being on-call is a critical duty that many operations and engineering teams must undertake in order to keep their services reliable and available.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] However, there are several pitfalls in the organization of on-call rotations and responsibilities that can lead to serious consequences for the services and for the teams if not avoided.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This chapter describes the primary tenets of the approach to on-call that Google’s Site Reliability Engineers (SREs) have developed over years, and explains how that approach has led to reliable services and sustainable workload over time.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Several professions require employees to perform some sort of on-call duty, which entails being available for calls during both working and nonworking hours.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In the IT context, on-call activities have historically been performed by dedicated Ops teams tasked with the primary responsibility of keeping the service(s) for which they are responsible in good health.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Many important services in Google, e.g., Search, Ads, and Gmail, have dedicated teams of SREs responsible for the performance and reliability of these services.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Thus, SREs are on-call for the services they support.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The SRE teams are quite different from purely operational teams in that they place heavy emphasis on the use of engineering to approach problems.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] These problems, which typically fall in the operational domain, exist at a scale that would be intractable without software engineering solutions.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] To enforce this type of problem solving, Google hires people with a diverse background in systems and software engineering into SRE teams.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] We cap the amount of time SREs spend on purely operational work at 50%; at minimum, 50% of an SRE’s time should be allocated to engineering projects that further scale the impact of the team through automation, in addition to improving the service.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This section describes the typical activities of an on-call engineer and provides some background for the rest of the chapter.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] As the guardians of production systems, on-call engineers take care of their assigned operations by managing outages that affect the team and performing and/or vetting production changes.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] When on-call, an engineer is available to perform operations on production systems within minutes, according to the paging response times agreed to by the team and the business system owners.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Typical values are 5 minutes for user-facing or otherwise highly time-critical services, and 30 minutes for less time-sensitive systems.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The company provides the page-receiving device, which is typically a phone.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Google has flexible alert delivery systems that can dispatch pages via multiple mechanisms (email, SMS, robot call, app) across multiple devices.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Response times are related to desired service availability, as demonstrated by the following simplistic example: if a user-facing system must obtain 4 nines of availability in a given quarter (99.99%), the allowed quarterly downtime is around 13 minutes (Availability Table).
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This constraint implies that the reaction time of on-call engineers has to be in the order of minutes (strictly speaking, 13 minutes).
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For systems with more relaxed SLOs, the reaction time can be on the order of tens of minutes.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] As soon as a page is received and acknowledged, the on-call engineer is expected to triage the problem and work toward its resolution, possibly involving other team members and escalating as needed.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Nonpaging production events, such as lower priority alerts or software releases, can also be handled and/or vetted by the on-call engineer during business hours.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] These activities are less urgent than paging events, which take priority over almost every other task, including project work.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For more insight on interrupts and other non-paging events that contribute to operational load, see Dealing with Interrupts.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Many teams have both a primary and a secondary on-call rotation.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The distribution of duties between the primary and the secondary varies from team to team.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] One team might employ the secondary as a fall-through for the pages the primary on-call misses.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Another team might specify that the primary on-call handles only pages, while the secondary handles all other non-urgent production activities.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In teams for which a secondary rotation is not strictly required for duty distribution, it is common for two related teams to serve as secondary on-call for each other, with fall-through handling duties.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This setup eliminates the need for an exclusive secondary on-call rotation.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] There are many ways to organize on-call rotations; for detailed analysis, refer to the "Oncall" chapter of [Lim14].
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] SRE teams have specific constraints on the quantity and quality of on-call shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The quantity of on-call can be calculated by the percent of time spent by engineers on on-call duties.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The quality of on-call can be calculated by the number of incidents that occur during an on-call shift.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] SRE managers have the responsibility of keeping the on-call workload balanced and sustainable across these two axes.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] We strongly believe that the "E" in "SRE" is a defining characteristic of our organization, so we strive to invest at least 50% of SRE time into engineering: of the remainder, no more than 25% can be spent on-call, leaving up to another 25% on other types of operational, nonproject work.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Using the 25% on-call rule, we can derive the minimum number of SREs required to sustain a 24/7 on-call rotation.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Assuming that there are always two people on-call (primary and secondary, with different duties), the minimum number of engineers needed for on-call duty from a single-site team is eight: assuming week-long shifts, each engineer is on-call (primary or secondary) for one week every month.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For dual-site teams, a reasonable minimum size of each team is six, both to honor the 25% rule and to ensure a substantial and critical mass of engineers for the team.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] If a service entails enough work to justify growing a single-site team, we prefer to create a multi-site team.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] However, multi-site teams incur communication and coordination overhead.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Therefore, the decision to go multi-site or single-site should be based upon the trade-offs each option entails, the importance of the system, and the workload each system generates.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For each on-call shift, an engineer should have sufficient time to deal with any incidents and follow-up activities such as writing postmortems [Loo10].
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Let’s define an incident as a sequence of events and alerts that are related to the same root cause and would be discussed as part of the same postmortem.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] We’ve found that on average, dealing with the tasks involved in an on-call incident—root-cause analysis, remediation, and follow-up activities like writing a postmortem and fixing bugs—takes 6 hours.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] It follows that the maximum number of incidents per day is 2 per 12-hour on-call shift.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] If this limit is temporarily exceeded, e.g., for a quarter, corrective measures should be put in place to make sure that the operational load returns to a sustainable state (see Operational Overload and Embedding an SRE to Recover from Operational Overload).
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Adequate compensation needs to be considered for out-of-hours support.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Different organizations handle on-call compensation in different ways; Google offers time-off-in-lieu or straight cash compensation, capped at some proportion of overall salary.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The compensation cap represents, in practice, a limit on the amount of on-call work that will be taken on by any individual.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This compensation structure ensures incentivization to be involved in on-call duties as required by the team, but also promotes a balanced on-call work distribution and limits potential drawbacks of excessive on-call work, such as burnout or inadequate time for project work.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] As mentioned earlier, SRE teams support Google’s most critical systems.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Being an SRE on-call typically means assuming responsibility for user-facing, revenue-critical systems or for the infrastructure required to keep these systems up and running.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] SRE methodology for thinking about and tackling problems is vital for the appropriate operation of services.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] When one is dealing with the outages related to complex systems, the second of these options is more likely to produce better results and lead to well-planned incident handling.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] To make sure that the engineers are in the appropriate frame of mind to leverage the latter mindset, it’s important to reduce the stress related to being on-call.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Stress hormones like cortisol and corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) are known to cause behavioral consequences—including fear—that can impair cognitive functions and cause suboptimal decision making [Chr09].
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Under the influence of these stress hormones, the more deliberate cognitive approach is typically subsumed by unreflective and unconsidered (but immediate) action, leading to potential abuse of heuristics.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Heuristics are very tempting behaviors when one is on-call.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For example, when the same alert pages for the fourth time in the week, and the previous three pages were initiated by an external infrastructure system, it is extremely tempting to exercise confirmation bias by automatically associating this fourth occurrence of the problem with the previous cause.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] While intuition and quick reactions can seem like desirable traits in the middle of incident management, they have downsides.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Intuition can be wrong and is often less supportable by obvious data.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Thus, following intuition can lead an engineer to waste time pursuing a line of reasoning that is incorrect from the start.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Quick reactions are deep-rooted in habit, and habitual responses are unconsidered, which means they can be disastrous.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The ideal methodology in incident management strikes the perfect balance of taking steps at the desired pace when enough data is available to make a reasonable decision while simultaneously critically examining your assumptions.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] It’s important that on-call SREs understand that they can rely on several resources that make the experience of being on-call less daunting than it may seem.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The developer teams of SRE-supported systems usually participate in a 24/7 on-call rotation, and it is always possible to escalate to these partner teams when necessary.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The appropriate escalation of outages is generally a principled way to react to serious outages with significant unknown dimensions.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] When one is handling incidents, if the issue is complex enough to involve multiple teams or if, after some investigation, it is not yet possible to estimate an upper bound for the incident’s time span, it can be useful to adopt a formal incident-management protocol.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Google SRE uses the protocol described in Managing Incidents, which offers an easy-to-follow and well-defined set of steps that aid an on-call engineer to rationally pursue a satisfactory incident resolution with all the required help.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This protocol is internally supported by a web-based tool that automates most of the incident management actions, such as handing off roles and recording and communicating status updates.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] This tool allows incident managers to focus on dealing with the incident, rather than spending time and cognitive effort on mundane actions such as formatting emails or updating several communication channels at once.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Finally, when an incident occurs, it’s important to evaluate what went wrong, recognize what went well, and take action to prevent the same errors from recurring in the future.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] SRE teams must write postmortems after significant incidents and detail a full timeline of the events that occurred.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] By focusing on events rather than the people, these postmortems provide significant value.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Rather than placing blame on individuals, they derive value from the systematic analysis of production incidents.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Mistakes happen, and software should make sure that we make as few mistakes as possible.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Recognizing automation opportunities is one of the best ways to prevent human errors [Loo10].
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] As mentioned in Balanced On-Call, SREs spend at most 50% of their time on operational work.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] What happens if operational activities exceed this limit?
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The SRE team and leadership are responsible for including concrete objectives in quarterly work planning in order to make sure that the workload returns to sustainable levels.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Temporarily loaning an experienced SRE to an overloaded team, discussed in Embedding an SRE to Recover from Operational Overload, can provide enough breathing room so that the team can make headway in addressing issues.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Ideally, symptoms of operational overload should be measurable, so that the goals can be quantified (e.g., number of daily tickets < 5, paging events per shift < 2).
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Misconfigured monitoring is a common cause of operational overload.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Paging alerts should be aligned with the symptoms that threaten a service’s SLOs.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] All paging alerts should also be actionable.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Low-priority alerts that bother the on-call engineer every hour (or more frequently) disrupt productivity, and the fatigue such alerts induce can also cause serious alerts to be treated with less attention than necessary.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] See Dealing with Interrupts for further discussion.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] It is also important to control the number of alerts that the on-call engineers receive for a single incident.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Sometimes a single abnormal condition can generate several alerts, so it’s important to regulate the alert fan-out by ensuring that related alerts are grouped together by the monitoring or alerting system.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] If, for any reason, duplicate or uninformative alerts are generated during an incident, silencing those alerts can provide the necessary quiet for the on-call engineer to focus on the incident itself.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Noisy alerts that systematically generate more than one alert per incident should be tweaked to approach a 1:1 alert/incident ratio.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Doing so allows the on-call engineer to focus on the incident instead of triaging duplicate alerts.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Sometimes the changes that cause operational overload are not under the control of the SRE teams.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] For example, the application developers might introduce changes that cause the system to be more noisy, less reliable, or both.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In this case, it is appropriate to work together with the application developers to set common goals to improve the system.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In extreme cases, SRE teams may have the option to "give back the pager"—SRE can ask the developer team to be exclusively on-call for the system until it meets the standards of the SRE team in question.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Giving back the pager doesn’t happen very frequently, because it’s almost always possible to work with the developer team to reduce the operational load and make a given system more reliable.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In some cases, though, complex or architectural changes spanning multiple quarters might be required to make a system sustainable from an operational point of view.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] In such cases, the SRE team should not be subject to an excessive operational load.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Instead, it is appropriate to negotiate the reorganization of on-call responsibilities with the development team, possibly routing some or all paging alerts to the developer on-call.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Such a solution is typically a temporary measure, during which time the SRE and developer teams work together to get the service in shape to be on-boarded by the SRE team again.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Being on-call for a quiet system is blissful, but what happens if the system is too quiet or when SREs are not on-call often enough?
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] An operational underload is undesirable for an SRE team.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Being out of touch with production for long periods of time can lead to confidence issues, both in terms of overconfidence and underconfidence, while knowledge gaps are discovered only when an incident occurs.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] To counteract this eventuality, SRE teams should be sized to allow every engineer to be on-call at least once or twice a quarter, thus ensuring that each team member is sufficiently exposed to production.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] "Wheel of Misfortune" exercises (discussed in Accelerating SREs to On-Call and Beyond) are also useful team activities that can help to hone and improve troubleshooting skills and knowledge of the service.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Google also has a company-wide annual disaster recovery event called DiRT (Disaster Recovery Training) that combines theoretical and practical drills to perform multiday testing of infrastructure systems and individual services; see [Kri12].
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] The approach to on-call described in this chapter serves as a guideline for all SRE teams in Google and is key to fostering a sustainable and manageable work environment.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] Google’s approach to on-call has enabled us to use engineering work as the primary means to scale production responsibilities and maintain high reliability and availability despite the increasing complexity and number of systems and services for which SREs are responsible.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] While this approach might not be immediately applicable to all contexts in which engineers need to be on-call for IT services, we believe it represents a solid model that organizations can adopt in scaling to meet a growing volume of on-call work.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] 56An earlier version of this chapter appeared as an article in *;login:* (October 2015, vol.
[src:on-call-practices/being-on-call] 57For more discussion on the natural tension between SRE and product development teams, see Introduction.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] An incident is an event that could lead to loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services, or functions.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] **Incident management** (**IcM**) refers to the activities an organization undertakes to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent future recurrence.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] These incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), an incident management team (IMT), or Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Without effective incident management, an incident can disrupt business operations, information security, IT systems, employees, customers, or other vital business functions.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] An incident is an event that may lead to the loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services or functions.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incident management (IcM) is a term describing the activities of an organization to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent a future re-occurrence.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] If not managed, an incident can escalate into an emergency, crisis or disaster.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incident management is therefore the process of limiting the potential disruption caused by such an event, followed by a return to business as usual.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Physical incident management is the real-time response that may last for hours, days, or longer.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The United Kingdom Cabinet Office has produced the National Recovery Guidance (NRG), which is aimed at local responders as part of the implementation of the Civil Contingencies Act 2004 (CCA).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] It describes the response as the following: "Response encompasses the actions taken to deal with the immediate effects of an emergency.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] In many scenarios, it is likely to be relatively short and to last for a matter of hours or days – rapid implementation of arrangements for collaboration, coordination and communication is, therefore, vital.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Response encompasses the effort to deal not only with the direct effects of the emergency itself (eg fighting fires, rescuing individuals) but also the indirect effects (eg disruption, media interest)".
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] This again shows the importance of not just good planning but the effective allocation of resources to treat the risk.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incident management in critical infrastructure environments involves coordinated response activities designed to protect essential services whose disruption may impact public safety, economic stability, or national security.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Unlike incident management in purely informational or corporate IT contexts, critical infrastructure incidents often involve operational technology, physical processes, safety systems, and regulatory obligations.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Critical infrastructure incident management typically emphasizes early detection, structured escalation, cross-functional coordination, and continuity of operations.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incidents may originate from cyber events, physical failures, human error, natural hazards, or combined (hybrid) causes, requiring integrated response across engineering, operations, security, executive leadership, and external authorities.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Because infrastructure sectors are highly interdependent, incident management approaches in these environments often account for cascading effects across energy, communications, transportation, healthcare, and other essential services.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] As a result, planning and response activities commonly incorporate predefined roles, decision authorities, communication protocols, and recovery objectives aligned with safety and resilience requirements.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Today, an important role is played by a Computer Security Incident Response Team (CSIRT), due to the rise of internet crime, and is a common example of an incident faced by companies in developed nations all across the world.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] For example, if an organization discovers that an intruder has gained unauthorized access to a computer system, the CSIRT would analyze the situation, determine the breadth of the compromise, and take corrective action.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Currently, over half of the world's hacking attempts on Trans National Corporations (TNCs) have taken place in North America (57%).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] A Computer Security Incident Response team can provide a secure environment for an organization, and has become a large part of the design of many modern networking teams.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), or an incident management team (IMT).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] These are often designated beforehand or during the event and are placed in control of the organization while the incident is being addressed, to restore normal functions.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The incident commander manages the response to a security incident and leads the members of the incident response team(s) through the process, as defined by the Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Usually, as part of the wider management process in private organizations, incident management is followed by post-incident analysis where it is determined why the incident happened despite precautions and controls.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] This analysis is normally overseen by the leaders of the organization, with the view of preventing a repetition of the incident through precautionary measures and often changes in policy.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] This information is then used as feedback to further develop the security policy and/or its practical implementation.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] In the United States, the National Incident Management System, developed by the Department of Homeland Security, integrates effective practices in emergency management into a comprehensive national framework.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] This often results in a higher level of contingency planning, exercise and training, as well as an evaluation of the management of the incident.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incident management frameworks for critical infrastructure commonly follow a lifecycle-based approach that includes incident detection, classification, response coordination, containment, recovery, and post-incident review.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] These frameworks are designed to support timely decision-making while balancing safety, operational continuity, and regulatory compliance.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] In critical infrastructure contexts, such frameworks often integrate elements from emergency management systems, cybersecurity incident response practices, and operational risk management models.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The goal is to enable organizations to respond effectively under high-consequence conditions while maintaining control over complex technical and organizational dependencies.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Practitioner-oriented literature provides detailed guidance on applying lifecycle-based incident management frameworks within industrial and critical infrastructure environments, including considerations for operational technology, safety, and cross-sector coordination.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] During the root cause analysis, human factors should be assessed.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] James Reason conducted a study into the understanding of adverse effects of human factors.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The study found that major incident investigations, such as Piper Alpha and Kings Cross Underground Fire, made it clear that the causes of the accidents were distributed widely within and outside the organization.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] There are two types of events: active failure—an action that has immediate effects and has the likelihood to cause an accident—and latent or delayed action—events can take years to have an effect and are usually combined with triggering events that then cause the accident.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Latent failures are created as the result of decisions taken at the higher echelons of an organisation.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Their damaging consequences may lie dormant for a long time, only becoming evident when they combine with local triggering factors (e.g., the spring tide, the loading difficulties at Zeebrugge harbour, etc.) to breach the system's defences.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Decisions taken in the higher echelons of an organization can trigger the events towards an accident becoming more likely, the planning, scheduling, forecasting, designing, policymaking, etc., can have a slow burning effect.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The actual unsafe act that triggers an accident can be traced back through the organization and the subsequent failures can be exposed, showing the accumulation of latent failures within the system as a whole that led to the accident becoming more likely and ultimately happening.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Better improvement action can be applied, and reduce the likelihood of the event happening again.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] Incident management is an important part of IT service management (ITSM) process area.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The first goal of the incident management process is to restore a normal service operation as quickly as possible and to minimize the impact on business operations, thus ensuring that the best possible levels of service quality and availability are maintained.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] 'Normal service operation' is defined here as service operation within service-level agreement (SLA).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] It is one process area within the broader ITIL and ISO 20000 environment.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] an unplanned interruption to an IT service or reduction in the quality of an IT service or a failure of a Configuration Item that has not yet impacted an IT service (for example failure of one disk from a mirror set).
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The ITIL incident management process *ensures that normal service operation is restored as quickly as possible and the business impact is minimized.* **ITIL Service Operation*.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The HIPAA Breach Notification Rule further requires notification to affected individuals within 60 days when unsecured protected health information is compromised, with breaches affecting 500 or more individuals reported to HHS and the media.
[src:on-call-practices/incident-management] The proposed rule also mandates annual testing and revision of incident response and contingency plans.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The ICD-11 of the World Health Organization (WHO) describes **occupational burnout** as a work-related phenomenon resulting from chronic workplace stress that has not been successfully managed.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Occupational burnout is classified as an occupational phenomenon but is not recognized by the WHO as a medical or psychiatric condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Social psychologist Christina Maslach and colleagues made clear that burnout does not constitute "a single, one-dimensional phenomenon." However, national health bodies in some European countries do recognize it as such, and it is also independently recognized by some health practitioners.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Nevertheless, a body of evidence suggests that what is termed burnout is a depressive condition, that is to say, indistinct from, and overlaps with, depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Kaschka, Korczak, and Broich (2011) advanced the view that burnout is described in the Book of Exodus (18:17–18).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In the *New International Version* of the *Bible*, Moses' father-in-law said to Moses, "What you are doing is not good.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] You and these people who come to you will only wear yourselves out.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The work is too heavy for you; you cannot handle it alone." Gordon Parker suggested that the ancient European concept of acedia refers to burnout and not depression as many others believe.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] By 1834, the German concept of *Berufskrankheiten* (occupational diseases) had become established.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The concept reflected adverse work-related effects on mental and physical health.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Beard broadened the potential symptoms of neurasthenia such that the disorder could be the source of almost any symptom or behaviour.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Lipsitt would later wonder if the term "burnout" was similarly too broadly defined to be useful.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2017 the Dutch psychologist Wilmar Schaufeli pointed out similarities between Beard's concept of neurasthenia and that of the contemporary concept of occupational burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The rest cure was a commonly prescribed treatment for neurasthenia in the United States, particularly for women.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The American doctor Silas Weir Mitchell often prescribed this treatment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Other treatments included hypnosis, Paul Charles Dubois's cognitive behavioural therapy (this is distinct from and devised much earlier than Aaron Beck's cognitive behavioral therapy), and Otto Binswanger's life normalisation therapy.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1888, the English neurologist William Gowers coined the term *occupation neurosis* to describe cramps experienced by writers and pianists (repetitive strain injury), translating the German concept of *Beschäftigungsneurosen* (occupational diseases affecting the nerves).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The related term *occupational neurosis* came to include a wide range of work-caused anxieties and other mental problems.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] By the late 1930s, American health professionals had become widely acquainted with the condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It became known as *berufsneurose* in German.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] From 1915, the Japanese psychiatrist Shoma Morita developed Morita therapy to treat neurasthenia.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] He had come to have a different understanding of the condition than Beard, preferring to call it *shinkeishitsui*; he published two books about the condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1957, Swiss psychiatrist Paul Kielholz coined the term *Erschöpfungsdepression* [exhaustion-depression].
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The concept was one of a number of new depression-subtypes that gained traction in France and Germany during the 1960s.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1961, British author Graham Greene published the novel *A Burnt-Out Case*, the story of an architect who became disenchanted with the fame his achievements garnered for him and volunteered to work at a leper colony in the Congo.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1965, Kielholz publicised therapy for *Erschöpfungsdepression* in the German-speaking world through his book *Diagnose und Therapie der Depressionen für den Praktiker* [*Diagnosis and Treatment of Depression for the Practitioner*].
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] His work inspired further writing on the topic by German psychiatrist Volker Faust.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1968, the second edition of the American Psychiatric Association's (APA) *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual* (*DSM-II*) replaced "psychophysiologic nervous system reaction" with the condition *neurasthenic neurosis (neurasthenia)*.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1969, American prison official Harold B Bradley used the term *burnout* in a criminology paper to describe the fatigued staff at a centre for treating young adult offenders.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Bradley's article has been cited as the first known academic paper to use the term.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1974, Herbert Freudenberger, a German-born American clinical psychologist, used the term "burn-out" in his academic paper "Staff Burn-Out." The paper was based on his qualitative observations of the volunteer staff (including himself) at a free clinic for drug addicts.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] He characterized burnout by a set of symptoms that includes exhaustion resulting from work's excessive demands.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Other symptoms he identified were headaches, sleeplessness, "quickness to anger," and closed thinking.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] He observed that the burned-out worker "looks, acts, and seems depressed." After the publication of Freudenberger's paper, interest in the concept grew.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The American psychologist Christina Maslach described burnout in a 1976 magazine article as reflecting the impact of interpersonal stress on human service workers (e.g., social workers, psychiatrists, poverty lawyers, etc.).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The impact manifested itself in symptoms such as fatigue, quickness to anger, and cynical attitudes toward the people the service workers were supposed to help.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Also in 1976, Israeli-American psychologist Ayala Pines and American psychologist Elliot Aronson, using group workshops, began to treat people having symptoms of burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Pines collaborated with Maslach in writing essentially data-free papers about burnout in individuals who worked in day care centers and mental health facilities.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It abolished the concepts of neurasthenia and asthenic personality, both with the explanation "This DSM-II category was rarely used." Neither was directly replaced.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1981, Maslach and fellow American psychologist Susan E.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Jackson published an instrument for assessing occupational burnout, the Maslach Burnout Inventory (MBI).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It was the first such instrument of its kind, and soon became the most widely used measure of occupational burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The two researchers described occupational burnout in terms of emotional exhaustion, depersonalization (feeling low-empathy towards other people in an occupational setting), and reduced feelings of work-related accomplishment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1988, Pines and Aronson wrote the popular book *Career Burnout: Causes and Cures,* an updated version of a book they had published in April 1981 with American psychologist Ditsa Kafry.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The WHO's *ICD-10* (1994) removed the diagnosis of asthenic personality; the WHO, however, continued to include neurasthenia (F48.0).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1998, Swedish psychiatrists Marie Åsberg and Åke Nygren investigated a surge of depression-related health insurance claims in their country.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They found that the symptoms of many cases did not match the typical presentation of depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Complaints like fatigue and decreased cognitive ability dominated, and many believed their working conditions to be the cause.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2003, the American psychiatrists Philip M.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Van Liew advanced the view that the concept of burnout is largely bereft of meaning and has often come to refer to "stress-induced unhappiness" with one's job.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They also noted that burnout can mean "everything from fatigue to a major depression and now seems to have become an alternative word for depression but with less serious significance" (p.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2005, the Swedish Board of Health and Welfare created the national ICD condition of "exhaustion disorder" (F43.8A) as a specific "Other reactions to severe stress" (F43.8).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In December 2007, the Swiss Expert Network on Burnout (SEB) was established.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It has since held a number of symposia, and published recommendations for treating burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2015, French psychologist Renzo Bianchi and his colleagues published a literature review on the burnout–depression overlap (based on 92 studies) and concluded that the studies fail to demonstrate the nosological distinctiveness of the burnout phenomenon.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A number of papers followed that showed the overlap of burnout with depression, suggesting that burnout is a depressive condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Also in 2015, the WHO adopted a new conceptualization of "occupational burnout." The conceptualization was consistent with Maslach's.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2020, the Occupational Depression Inventory was published and was considered to be a potential replacement for burnout scales such as the MBI.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The WHO's *ICD-11* began official use in 2022.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Within this categorisation, the concept of neurasthenia became part of the new condition known as "bodily distress disorder" (6C20).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The WHO also modified their definition of burnout that year.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] This new edition additionally saw the WHO abolish nation-defined conditions, leading to Sweden's planned end to its specific recognition of exhaustion disorder in 2028.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The two main classification systems for psychiatric disorders are the APA's *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* (*DSM*, used in North America and elsewhere) and the WHO's *International Classification of Diseases* (*ICD*, used in Europe and elsewhere).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout is not recognized as a distinct mental disorder in the *DSM-5* (published in 2013).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Its definitions for Adjustment Disorders, and Unspecified Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorder have been said that in some cases reflect the condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The 2022 update of the *DSM*, the *DSM-5-TR*, did not include burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The *ICD-10* (1994–2021) classification "burn-out" as a type of non-medical life-management difficulty under code Z73.0.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2003, Liu and van Liew wrote that "the term burnout is used so frequently that it has lost much of its original meaning.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] As originally used, burnout meant a mild degree of stress-induced unhappiness.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The solutions ranged from a vacation to a sabbatical.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Ultimately, it was used to describe everything from fatigue to a major depression and now seems to have become an alternative word for depression, but with a less serious significance" (p.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The authors equated burnout with adjustment disorder with depressed mood.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] By 2003, the Royal Dutch Medical Association had defined *burnout* as a subtype of adjustment disorder as part of the *ICD-10* system.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In the Netherlands, *overspannenheid* (overstrain) is a condition that leads to *burnout*.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In that country, burnout is included in handbooks and medical staff are trained in its diagnosis and treatment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A reform of Dutch health insurance programs resulted in adjustment disorder treatment being removed from the compulsory basic package in 2012.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Practitioners were told that more serious cases of the condition may qualify for classification as depression or anxiety disorder.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A 2013 French study bearing on diagnosis compared the depressive symptom profiles of 46 depressed outpatients, an equal number of individuals, in this case teachers, with clinical burnout, and more than 400 burnout-free teachers.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The depressive symptom profiles of the depressed patients and the burnt-out teachers were highly similar but both groups had similarly and significantly higher levels of depressive symptoms than that of the teachers without clinical burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Several European countries have legally recognized burnout in some way, such as by providing workers' compensation payments.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Legal recognition for financial purposes, however, is not the same as medical recognition as a discrete disease.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] If, after treatment, a person with burnout continues to have persistent physical symptoms triggered by the condition, in Iceland the individual may be considered to have "somatic symptom disorder" (*DSM-5*) or "bodily distress disorder" (*ICD-11*).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2018) in a review of 182 studies of physician burnout identified 142 different definitions of burnout, underlining the great heterogeneity in diagnostic criteria for the condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] When they limited themselves to studies that used the canonical Maslach Burnout Inventory, the study team found 47 distinct definitions of burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Marked differences among researchers' conceptualizations of what constitutes burnout have underlined the absence of a consensus definition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A new version of the *ICD*, *ICD-11*, was released in June 2018, for first use in January 2022.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In a statement made in May 2019, the WHO said "Burn-out is included in the 11th Revision of the International Classification of Diseases (ICD-11) as an occupational phenomenon.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It is not classified as a medical condition." The *ICD-11* also has the medical condition "6B4Y Other specified disorders specifically associated with stress," which is the equivalent of the *ICD-10'*s F43.8.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Further detail about the varied ways clinicians and others used the then-current *ICD* and *DSM* classifications with burnout was published by Dutch psychologist Arno Van Dam in 2021.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The US government's National Institutes of Health includes the condition as "psychological burnout" in its index of the National Library of Medicine, and provides a number of synonyms.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A number of instruments have been developed to assess work-related burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The National Academy of Medicine has created an inventory of burnout scales.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The core of all of the abovementioned conceptualizations, including that of Freudenberger, is exhaustion.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1981, Maslach and Jackson published the first widely used instrument for assessing burnout, the Maslach Burnout Inventory (MBI).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It remains by far the most commonly used instrument to assess the condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The MBI originally focused on human service professionals (e.g., teachers, social workers).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Since that time, the MBI has been used for a wider variety of workers (e.g., healthcare workers).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The instrument or its variants are now employed with job incumbents working in many other occupations.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Its cost may be a disincentive that discourages graduate students and young assistant professors from using it.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] There are other conceptualizations of burnout that differ from the conceptualization suggested by Maslach and adopted by the WHO.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1999, Demerouti and Bakker, with their Oldenburg Burnout Inventory (OLBI), conceptualized burnout in terms of exhaustion and disengagement, linking their conceptualization to the job demands–resources model.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2005, Kristensen et al. released the public domain Copenhagen Burnout Inventory (CBI).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They argued that the definition of burnout should be limited to the fatigue/exhaustion continuum.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2006, Shirom and Melamed with their Shirom-Melamed Burnout Measure (SMBM) conceptualized burnout in terms of physical exhaustion, cognitive weariness, and emotional exhaustion.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The SMBM's emotional exhaustion subscale more clearly embodies Maslach's concept of depersonalization than her concept of emotional exhaustion.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] This measure has seen some use in Sweden.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2014, Besèr et al. published the Karolinska Exhaustion Disorder Scale (KEDS), which is used mainly in Sweden.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It was designed to measure the symptoms defined by the ICD-10-SE's category for exhaustion disorder.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The authors believed that those with the disorder were often initially depressed, but that this soon passed.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The core symptoms of the disorder were deemed to be "exhaustion, cognitive problems, sleep disturbance".
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The authors also believed that the condition was clearly differentiated from both depression and anxiety.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] There are other conceptualizations of burnout embodied in other instruments, including the Hamburg Burnout Inventory, the Burnout Assessment Tool, the Burnout Measure, and the Meier Burnout Assessment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 1999, Wilmar Schaufeli and Arnold Bakker published the Utrecht Work Engagement Scale (UWES), an instrument that uses a conceptualisation similar to that of the MBI.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] However the UWES measures vigour, dedication and absorption, positive counterparts (or polar opposites) of the high-burnout endpoints of the MBI's subscales.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In 2010, researchers at the Mayo Clinic used portions of the MBI, along with other comprehensive assessments, to develop the Well-Being Index, a nine-item self-assessment tool designed to measure burnout and other dimensions of distress in healthcare workers specifically.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The measure has mainly been used in the United States.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The Occupational Depression Inventory (ODI) was published in 2020.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The measure covers the nine main symptoms of depression that individuals ascribe to their jobs and quantifies the severity of those work-attributed symptoms.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The ODI also generates provisional diagnoses of job-ascribed depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The instrument exhibits robust psychometric properties.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The ODI is the only instrument that assesses work-related suicidal thoughts, a particularly important symptom calling for immediate attention.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Available evidence indicates that burnout scales have very high correlations with the ODI, correlations that cannot be explained by item content overlap, suggesting that the ODI is a suitable replacement for burnout scales like the MBI.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout in certain groups of people has received focused attention.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout is thought to affect caregivers.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In the ICD-11, in the description for code QF27 "Difficulty or need for assistance at home and no other household member able to render care" the term "caregiver burnout" is given as a synonym.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Aylala Malach-Pines (who also published as Ayala Pines) advanced the view that burnout can occur in connection to the spousal role.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Academic burnout refers to a form of burnout experienced by university students as a result of prolonged academic stress and demands.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It is characterized by emotional exhaustion, reduced motivation toward academic tasks, and a decreased sense of competence in one's studies.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout in teachers represents a type of occupational burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Athlete burnout, which burdens athletes' mental health and well-being, can, in extreme cases, lead to athletes terminating their participation in a physical activity they once enjoyed.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Autistic people are known to experience a state of mental, emotional, or physical exhaustion referred to as autistic burnout because of the general stress involved in masking of autistic traits and behavior and the strains associated with living in an unaccommodating environment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Autistic burnout is considered to be distinct from occupational burnout in both etiology and presentation.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The concept of autistic burnout became much more common on Twitter in 2017–18, and subsequently attracted more academic research.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The establishing paper on the subject was published by American systems scientist Dora Raymaker et al. in June 2020.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Liu and van Liew advanced the view that the concept of burnout has been overused and "lost much of its original meaning." They wrote that originally the term referred to a mild degree of unhappiness caused by job stress.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They suggested that the contemporary use of the term *burnout* can refer to conditions that range from fatigue to major depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They wrote that the term has served as a euphemism for depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A body of evidence indicates that burnout is etiologically, clinically, and nosologically similar to depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In a study that directly compared depressive symptoms in burned out workers and clinically depressed patients, no diagnostically significant differences were found between the two groups; burned out workers reported as many depressive symptoms as clinically depressed patients.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2014) showed that about 90% of workers with very high scores on the MBI meet diagnostic criteria for depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The view that burnout is a depressive phenomenon has found support.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Some authors have recommended that the nosological concept of burnout be revised or even abandoned entirely given that it is not a distinct disorder and that there is little agreement on burnout's diagnostic criteria.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The advantage of ESEM bifactor analysis, which combines the best features of exploratory and confirmatory factor analysis, is that it provides a granular look at item-construct relationships, without falling into traps earlier burnout researchers fell into.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Maslach advanced the idea that burnout should not be viewed as a depressive condition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Recent evidence, based on factor-analytic and meta-analytic findings, calls into question this supposition.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout is also now often seen as involving the full array of depressive symptoms (e.g., low mood, cognitive alterations, sleep disturbance).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Kakiashvili et al. argued that although burnout and depression have overlapping symptoms, endocrine evidence suggests that the disorders' biological bases are different.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They argued that antidepressants should not be used by people with burnout because the medications can make the underlying hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis dysfunction worse.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Others have found Kakiashvili et al.'s argument specious.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Despite its name, depression with atypical features, which is seen in the above table, is not a rare form of depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The cortisol profile in atypical depression, in contrast to that of melancholic depression, is similar to the cortisol profile found in burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Commentators advanced the view that burnout differs from depression because the cortisol profile of burnout differs from that of melancholic depression; however, as the above table indicates, burnout's cortisol profile is similar to that of atypical depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Evidence suggests that the etiology of burnout is multifactorial, with personality factors playing an important, long-overlooked role.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The researchers identified the prominent personality factor neuroticism in the development of burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Cognitive dispositional factors implicated in depression have also been found to be implicated in burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Burnout is thought to occur when there is a mismatch between the job and the worker.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A common type of mismatch is work overload.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] For example, work overload can occur when a worker survives a round of layoffs, but after the layoffs the worker is doing too much with too few resources.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In the context of downsizing, an organization does not ordinarily narrow its goals, although fewer employees are available to meet those goals.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The research on downsizing indicates that it has more destructive effects on the health of the workers who survive the layoffs than just its effect on burnout; these health effects include increased levels of sickness and greater risk of mortality.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The job demands–resources model has implications for burnout, as measured by the Oldenburg Burnout Inventory (OLBI).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Physical and psychological job demands were concurrently associated with the exhaustion, as measured by the OLBI.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Lack of job resources was associated with the disengagement component of the OLBI.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Maslach and her colleagues (2001) identified six risk factors for burnout: mismatch in workload, mismatch in control, lack of appropriate awards, loss of a sense of positive connection with others in the workplace, perceived lack of fairness, and conflict between values.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Although job stress has long been viewed as the main determinant of burnout, recent meta-analytic findings indicate that job stress is at best a weak predictor of burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] These findings question one of the most central assumptions of burnout research.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] It has long been known that the personality dimension neuroticism is a strong predictor of burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In addition to broad these personality traits research suggests that elevated symptoms of attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) may represent an additional individual vulnerability factor for burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] ADHD-related difficulties may increase susceptibility to stress in cognitively demanding work environments.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2023) found a wide range of symptoms in individuals who were formally diagnosed with exhaustion disorder.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The most commonly reported symptoms among people suffering with the disorder were tiredness, lack of energy, difficulty recovering from exertion, poor general cognitive functioning, memory problems, and difficulty coping with perceived stressors and demands.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Some research indicates that burnout is associated with reduced job performance, coronary heart disease, and mental health problems.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Emotional symptoms associated with occupational burnout include a lack of interest in work, reduced performance, feelings of helplessness, and trouble sleeping.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Physical symptoms such as aches and pains, palpitations, gastrointestinal problems, vertigo or increased sensitivity to sound.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Research on dentists and physicians suggests that burnout is a depressive syndrome.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Thus reduced job performance and cardiovascular risk could be related to burnout because of burnout's tie to depression.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Behavioral signs of occupational burnout are demonstrated through cynicism within workplace relationships with coworkers, clients, and the organization itself.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Forced overtime, heavy workloads, and frenetic work paces give rise to debilitating repetitive stress injuries, on-the-job accidents, over-exposure to toxic substances, and other dangerous work conditions.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Williams and Strasser suggested that healthcare workers have focused much attention on the workplace risk factors for heart disease and other illnesses, but have underemphasized work-related depression risk.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Other effects of burnout can manifest as lower energy and productivity levels, with workers observed to be consistently late for work and feeling a sense of dread upon arriving.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They can suffer concentration problems, forgetfulness, increased frustration, and/or feelings of being overwhelmed.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They may complain and feel negative, or feel apathetic and believe they have little impact on their coworkers and environment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Occupational burnout is also associated with absenteeism, other time missed from work, and thoughts of quitting.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Emerging research has also examined whether burnout is associated with maladaptive coping behaviours.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A large study of working adults found that higher levels of burnout were associated with more frequent use of substances intended to enhance cognitive performance, particularly legal substances.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In this study, burnout statistically mediated the association between elevated ADHD symptoms and substance use frequency, suggesting that stress-related exhaustion may be linked to increased reliance on pharmacological coping strategies in demanding work environments.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] These findings mirror earlier research suggesting similar patterns.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] For example, a cross-sectional study of junior physicians in Germany reported that higher burnout levels were associated with prior off-prescription stimulant use for performance enhancement.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] As in depression, chronic burnout is also associated with cognitive impairments in memory and attention.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Research suggests that burnout can manifest differently between genders, with higher levels of depersonalisation among men and increased emotional exhaustion among women.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Other research suggests that people revealing a history of occupational burnout face future hiring discrimination.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] There are thought to be three general types of workplace prevention-related interventions.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Primary prevention-type interventions are aimed preventing health-damaging workplace stressors from developing in the first place or, if they are present, removing them from the workplace.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Secondary prevention has an early-detection purpose and is aimed at helping workers who manifest the beginnings of a health problem before that problem becomes full blown.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Tertiary prevention-type interventions are designed to help workers who have already experienced significant health problems.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Maslach suggested that preventing burnout requires a combination of organizational change and worker education.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] She and her co-authors argued that burnout can occur in connection to six areas of work life: workload, control, reward, community, fairness, and values.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] For example, with regard to workload, an organization should ensure that a worker has adequate resources to meet job demands.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] With regard to values, clearly stated ethical organizational values are important for employee well-being and commitment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Supportive leadership and relationships with colleagues are also helpful.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In one study employees met weekly to discuss and attempt to resolve perceived inequities in their job.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The intervention was associated with decreases in exhaustion over time but not cynicism or inefficacy, suggesting that a broader approach is required.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) initiatives are considered a resource which counteracts the stress effects of job demands, lowering employee burnout by boosting happiness, resilience and capitalizing altruism.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Establishing a sense of psychological safety (the belief that it is safe to speak up) in an organisation helps prevent burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Increasing workers' control over their work tasks is another intervention that can reduce exhaustion and cynicism.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Despite the above recommendations, high-quality research on burnout prevention with random allocation of experimental units (either individual workers or organizational units) to intervention and control conditions has been relatively rare.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] For example, Richardson and Rothstein's (2008) meta-analysis of primary workplace interventions included only two high-quality studies that addressed burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In their meta-analysis, Estevez Corres et al.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2021) identified only eight high-quality primary prevention studies devoted to reducing emotional exhaustion in "high-stress jobs"; fewer high-quality primary prevention studies were devoted to depersonalization and reduced accomplishment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] In a qualitative study, Meluch (2023), found that disclosing feelings of job burnout tends to make employees feel vulnerable.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] She also found that the perceived judgment of coworkers towards burnout is worrisome.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Kim and Lee recommended that organizations provide timely accurate information on activities and policies in order to minimize emotional exhaustion.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Van der Klink and van Dijk (2003) suggested stress inoculation training, cognitive restructuring, and graded activity to help workers with burnout symptoms, although insufficient high-quality research has been carried out on their efficacy.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2007) listed a number of common secondary and tertiary interventions, including treatment of any outstanding medical conditions, stress management, time management, depression treatment, psychotherapies, ergonomic improvement as well as occupational therapy, physical exercise and relaxation.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Mindfulness therapy has been used to help with occupational burnout in medical practitioners.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Additional prevention methods include: starting the day with a relaxing ritual; yoga; adopting healthy eating, exercising, and sleeping habits; setting boundaries; taking breaks from technology; nourishing one's creative side, and learning how to manage stress.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Farber (2000), writing about educators, suggested that strategies such as setting achievable goals, focusing on the value of the work, and finding better ways of doing the job can help teachers experiencing occupational stress.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Some secondary interventions can improve conditions at work by addressing work-life balance.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The ways in which people spend their non-work time can help to prevent burnout and improve health and well-being.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Training employees in ways to manage stress in the workplace has been thought to reduce burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] One study suggests that social-cognitive processes such as commitment to work, self-efficacy, learned resourcefulness, and hope may insulate individuals from experiencing occupational burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Kakiashvili et al. wrote that "medical treatment of burnout is mostly symptomatic: it involves measures to prevent and treat the symptoms." The authors reported that the use of pharmacotherapy to treat stress-related burnout is effective, but does nothing to change the sources of stress.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] They reported that the exhaustion and poor sleep that are part of burnout are best treated with cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT).
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2020) found that for workers with exhaustion disorder, CBT was better than a Return to Work Intervention (RTW-I) for reducing stress.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The researchers also found that people who were primarily experiencing symptoms of depression, anxiety, or insomnia, CBT reduced total time away from work. van Dam et al.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2012) had also earlier found that CBT was an effective treatment.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] (2021) found that the most useful treatment strategies appear to be talking to someone and seeking support, walking or other exercise, mindfulness and meditation, improving sleep, and leaving work completely or taking time off work.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The Royal Dutch College of General Practiconers recommend a three-stage treatment process, made up of a crisis phase, a problem and solution stage, and an application stage.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] The Gothenburg regional government's Institute for Stress Medicine reports that "[r]ecovery [from exhaustion disorder] is found in what is undemanding and joyful, and what that is varies greatly between individuals.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] Despite the above recommendations, high-quality research (e.g., random allocation to experimental and control groups) has been relatively rare in secondary and tertiary prevention-related interventions aimed at reducing symptoms of occupational burnout.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] One study suggests that cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT), which was developed to treat depression, can help some workers with symptoms of occupational burnout although high-quality research on the application of CBT to treating burnout has been sparse.
[src:on-call-practices/occupational-burnout] A shortcoming of CBT and other tertiary interventions is that they help to restructure the thinking of the worker/patient but do not change the adverse working conditions that give rise to the symptoms.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A **schedule**, often called a **rota** or a **roster**, is a list of employees, and associated information e.g. location, department, working times, responsibilities for a given time period e.g. week, month or sports season.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A schedule is necessary for the day-to-day operation of many businesses e.g. retail store, manufacturing facility and some offices.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] The process of creating a schedule is called **scheduling**.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] An effective workplace schedule balances the needs of stakeholders such as management, employees and customers.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A *daily* schedule is usually ordered chronologically, which means the first employees working that day are listed at the top, followed by the employee who comes in next, etc.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A *weekly* or *monthly* schedule is usually ordered alphabetically, employees being listed on the left hand side of a grid, with the days of the week on the top of the grid.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] In shift work, a schedule usually employs a recurring shift plan.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A schedule is most often created by a manager.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] In larger operations, a human resources manager or scheduling specialist may be solely dedicated to creating and maintaining the schedule.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A schedule by this definition is sometimes referred to as workflow.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Software is often used to enable organizations to better manage staff scheduling.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Organizations commonly use spreadsheet software or employee scheduling software to create and manage shifts, assignments, and employee preferences.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] For large organisations employee scheduling can be complex , and optimising this is framed as the nurse scheduling problem in operations Research.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Advanced employee scheduling software also provides ways to connect with the staff, ask for their preferences and communicate the schedule to them.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] An oncall shift, or on-call scheduling, is a practice that requires employees to be available to be called onto last-minute shifts without pre-scheduling.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Flexible self-scheduling is a practice used when a manager defines scheduling needs based on demand, but allows employees to select, trade, and fill shifts themselves.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Allowing schedules to be created faster, with less effort, and gives hourly employees more control over their work life.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] A fixed schedule is a workplace scheduling arrangement in which employees work the same set days and hours each week, with little or no variation over time.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Both the start and end times, as well as the specific days worked, remain consistent throughout the scheduling period.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Fixed schedules can be applied to both full-time and part-time roles across a variety of industries.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] This consistency provides several advantages, including increased predictability for employees, which enables easier planning of personal commitments and supports improved work-life balance.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] It can also contribute to administrative efficiency for employers, as schedules do not need to be changed frequently.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Regular work groups or teams can develop stronger collaboration and communication when working together at fixed times.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] In certain sectors, such as retail, manufacturing, or office-based environments, fixed schedules help streamline operations and foster routine.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] However, fixed schedules may offer limited flexibility for employees who require variable hours and may not optimally address fluctuating staffing needs in workplaces with unpredictable or seasonal demands.
[src:on-call-practices/on-call] Some employees may also find the lack of variation monotonous over extended periods.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The shift plan or rota is the central component of a shift schedule.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The schedule includes considerations of shift overlap, shift change times and alignment with the clock, vacation, training, shift differentials, holidays, etc., whereas the shift plan determines the sequence of work and free days within a shift system.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The most common plan for eight-hour workdays is the *three-shift plan*, where each day is divided into three eight-hour blocks, with the first shift beginning in the morning, and each worker works during the same block every workday.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Rotation of shifts can be fast, in which a worker changes shifts more than once a week, or slow, in which a worker changes shifts less than once a week.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Rotation can also be forward, when a subsequent shift starts later, or backward, when a subsequent shift starts earlier.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Evidence supports forward rotating shifts are more adaptable for shift workers' circadian physiology.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] One main concern of shift workers is knowing their schedule more than two weeks at a time.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] When on a rotating or ever changing shift, workers have to worry about daycare, personal appointments, and running their households.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Many already work more than an eight-hour shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Some evidence suggests giving employees schedules more than a month in advance would give proper notice and allow planning, their stress level would be reduced.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The 42-hour work-week allows for the most even distribution of work time.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] A 3:1 ratio of work days to days off is most effective for eight-hour shifts, and a 2:2 ratio of work days to days off is most effective for twelve-hour shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Eight-hour shifts and twelve-hour shifts are common in manufacturing and health care.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Twelve-hour shifts are also used with a very slow rotation in the petroleum industry.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Twenty-four-hour shifts are common in health care and emergency services.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The practices and policies put in place by managers of round-the-clock or 24/7 operations can significantly influence shift worker alertness (and hence safety) and performance.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Multiple factors need to be considered when developing optimal shift work schedules, including shift timing, length, frequency and length of breaks during shifts, shift succession, worker commute time, as well as the mental and physical stress of the job.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Mandating a minimum of 10 hours between shifts is an effective strategy to encourage adequate sleep for workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Allowing frequent breaks and scheduling 8- or 10-hour shifts instead of 12-hour shifts can also minimize fatigue and help to mitigate the negative health effects of shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Even though studies support 12-hour shifts are associated with increased occupational injuries and accident (higher rates with subsequent, successive shifts), a synthesis of evidence cites the importance of all factors when considering the safety of a shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Algorithmic scheduling of shift work can lead to what has been colloquially termed as "clopening" where the shift-worker has to work the closing shift of one day and the opening shift of the next day back-to-back resulting in short rest periods between shifts and fatigue.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Co-opting employees to fill the shift roster helps to ensure that the human costs are taken into account in a way which is hard for an algorithm to do as it would involve knowing the constraints and considerations of each individual shift worker and assigning a cost metric to each of those factors.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift based hiring which is a recruitment concept that hires people for individual shifts, rather than hiring employees before scheduling them into shifts enables shift workers to indicate their preferences and availability for unfilled shifts through a shift-bidding mechanism.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Through this process, the shift hours are evened out by human-driven market mechanism rather than an algorithmic process.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The shift work system in modern industrial manufacturing originated in the late 18th century.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The Cromford Mill, starting from 1772, ran day and night with two twelve-hour shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work was once characteristic primarily of the manufacturing industry, where it has a clear effect of increasing the use that can be made of capital equipment and allows for up to three times the production compared to just a day shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] It contrasts with the use of overtime to increase production at the margin.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Both approaches incur higher wage costs.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Although 2nd-shift worker efficiency levels are typically 3–5% below 1st shift, and 3rd shift 4–6% below 2nd shift, the productivity level, i.e. cost per employee, is often 25% to 40% lower on 2nd and 3rd shifts due to fixed costs which are "paid" by the first shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] It is estimated that 15–20% of workers in industrialized countries are employed in shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work is common in the transportation sector as well.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Some of the earliest instances appeared with the railroads, where freight trains have clear tracks to run on at night.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work is also the norm in fields related to public protection and healthcare, such as law enforcement, emergency medical services, firefighting, security and hospitals.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work is a contributing factor in many cases of medical errors.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work has often been common in the armed forces.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Military personnel, pilots, and others that regularly change time zones while performing shift work experience jet lag and consequently suffer sleep disorders.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Those in the field of meteorology, such as the National Weather Service and private forecasting companies, also use shift work, as constant monitoring of the weather is necessary.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Much of the Internet services and telecommunication industry relies on shift work to maintain worldwide operations and uptime.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Service industries now increasingly operate on some shift system; for example a restaurant or convenience store will normally be open on most days for much longer than a working day.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work increases the risk for the development of many disorders.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work increases the risk of sleep disorders.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work sleep disorder is a circadian rhythm sleep disorder characterized by insomnia, excessive sleepiness, or both.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work is considered essential for the diagnosis.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The health consequences of shift work may depend on chronotype, that is, being a day person or a night person, and what shift a worker is assigned to.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] When the individual's chronotype is the opposite of shift timing (e.g., a day person working night shift), there is a greater risk of circadian rhythm disruption.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Artificial lighting may additionally contribute to disturbed homeostasis.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Nighttime workers sleep an average of one to four hours less than daytime workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The risk of diabetes mellitus type 2 is increased in shift workers, especially men.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] People working rotating shifts are more vulnerable than others.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Working rotating shift work regularly during a two-year interval has been associated with a 9% increased the risk of early menopause compared to women who work no rotating shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The increased risk among rotating night shift workers was 25% among women predisposed to earlier menopause.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Early menopause can lead to a host of other problems later in life.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] A recent study, found that women who worked rotating night shifts for more than six years, 11% experienced a shortened lifespan.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work increases the risk of obesity, metabolic disorders, gastrointestinal disorders, musculoskeletal disorders, and reproductive disorders.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The WHO's International Agency for Research on Cancer listed "shift work that involves circadian disruption" as probably carcinogenic.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Women whose work involves night shifts have a 48% increased risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] This may be due to alterations in circadian rhythm: melatonin, a known tumor suppressor, is generally produced at night and late shifts may disrupt its production.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Women who worked rotating night shifts for more than 15 years also experienced a 25% higher risk of death due to lung cancer.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work may also increase the risk of other types of cancer.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work may also increase a person's risk of smoking.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work increases the risk of heart attacks.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work also can worsen chronic diseases, digestive diseases, heart disease, hypertension, asthma, and any health conditions that are treated with medications affected by the circadian cycle.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] One study suggests that, for those working a night shift (such as 23:00 to 07:00), it may be advantageous to sleep in the evening (14:00 to 22:00) rather than the morning (08:00 to 16:00).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The study's evening sleep subjects had 37% fewer episodes of attention impairment than the morning sleepers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] There are four major determinants of cognitive performance and alertness in healthy shift-workers: circadian phase, sleep inertia, acute sleep deprivation and chronic sleep deficit.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] According to data from the National Health Interview Survey and the Occupational Health Supplement, 27% of all U.S. workers in 2015 worked an alternative shift (not a regular day shift) and 7% frequently worked a night shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Prevalence rates were higher for workers aged 18–29 compared to other ages.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Those with an education level beyond high school had a lower prevalence rate of alternative shifts compared to workers with less education.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Among all occupations, protective service occupations had the highest prevalence of working an alternative shift (54%).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] One of the ways in which working alternative shifts can impair health is through decreasing sleep opportunities.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Among all workers, those who usually worked the night shift had a much higher prevalence of short sleep duration (44.0%, representing approximately 2.2 million night shift workers) than those who worked the day shift (28.8%, representing approximately 28.3 million day shift workers).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] An especially high prevalence of short sleep duration was reported by night shift workers in the transportation and warehousing (69.7%) and health-care and social assistance (52.3%) industries.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Missing income is also a large part of shift worker.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Several companies run twenty-four-hour shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Most of the work is done during the day.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] When the work dries up, it usually is the second and third shift workers who pay the price.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] They are told to punch out early or use paid time off if they have any to make up the difference in their paychecks.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] That practice costs the average worker $92.00 a month.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] A cross-sectional study investigated the relationship between several sleep assessment criteria and different shift work schedules (3-day, 6-day, 9-day and 21-day shift) and a control group of day shift work in Korean firefighters.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The results found that all shift work groups exhibited significant decreased total sleep time (TST) and decreased sleep efficiency in the night shift but efficiency increased in the rest day.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Between-group analysis of the different shift work groups revealed that day shift sleep efficiency was significantly higher in the 6-day shift while night shift sleep efficiency was significantly lower in the 21-day shift in comparison to other shift groups (*p* < 0.05).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Overall, night shift sleep quality was worse in shift workers than those who just worked the day shift, whereas 6-day shift provided better sleep quality compared to the 21-day shift.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Though shift work itself remains necessary in many occupations, employers can alleviate some of the negative health consequences of shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The United States National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health recommends employers avoid quick shift changes and any rotating shift schedules should rotate forward.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Employers should also attempt to minimize the number of consecutive night shifts, long work shifts and overtime work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] A poor work environment can exacerbate the strain of shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Adequate lighting, clean air, proper heat and air conditioning, and reduced noise can all make shift work more bearable for workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Different shift schedules will have different impacts on the health of a shift worker.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The way the shift pattern is designed affects how shift workers sleep, eat and take holidays.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Some shift patterns can exacerbate fatigue by limiting rest, increasing stress, overworking staff or disrupting their time off.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] This includes blocking out noise and light during sleep, maintaining a regular, predictable sleep routine, avoiding heavy foods and alcohol before sleep, and sleeping in a comfortable, cool environment.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Alcohol consumption, caffeine consumption and heavy meals in the few hours before sleep can worsen shift work sleep disorders.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Exercise in the three hours before sleep can make it difficult to fall asleep.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Free online training programs are available to educate workers and managers about the risks associated with shift work and strategies they can use to prevent these.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Melatonin may increase sleep length during both daytime and nighttime sleep in people who work night shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Zopiclone has also been investigated as a potential treatment, but it is unclear if it is effective in increasing daytime sleep time in shift workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] There are, however, no reports of adverse effects.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Modafinil and R-modafinil are useful to improve alertness and reduce sleepiness in shift workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Modafinil has a low risk of abuse compared to other similar agents.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] However, 10% more participants reported adverse effects (nausea and headache) while taking modafinil.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] In post-marketing surveillance, modafinil was associated with Stevens–Johnson syndrome.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The European Medicines Agency withdrew the license for modafinil for shift workers for the European market because it judged that the benefits did not outweigh the adverse effects.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Using caffeine and naps before night shifts can decrease sleepiness.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Caffeine has also been shown to reduce errors made by shift workers.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work has been shown to negatively affect workers, and has been classified as a specific disorder (shift work sleep disorder).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Circadian disruption by working at night causes symptoms like excessive sleepiness at work and sleep disturbances.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work sleep disorder also creates a greater risk for human error at work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Shift work disrupts cognitive ability and flexibility and impairs attention, motivation, decision making, speech, vigilance, and overall performance.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Compared with the day shift, injuries and accidents have been estimated to increase by 15% on evening shifts and 28% on night shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Longer shifts are also associated with more injuries and accidents: 10-hour shifts had 13% more and 12-hour shifts had 28% more than 8-hour shifts.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Other studies have shown a link between fatigue and workplace injuries and accidents.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Workers with sleep deprivation are far more likely to be injured or involved in an accident.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] To mitigate the negative effects of shift work on safety and health, many countries have enacted regulations on shift work.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The EU directive also limits night work involving "special hazards or heavy physical or mental strain" to an average of eight hours in any 24-hour period.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The EU directive allows for limited derogations from the regulation, and special provisions allow longer working hours for transportation and offshore workers, fishing vessel workers, and doctors in training (see also medical resident work hours).
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] For fewer operational errors, the FAA goal calls for Flight Controllers to be on duty for 5 to 6 hours per shift, with the remaining shift time devoted to meals and breaks.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] For aircraft pilots, the actual time at the controls (flight time) is limited to 8 or 9 hours, depending on the time of day.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] Fatigue due to shift work has contributed to several industrial disasters, including the Three Mile Island accident, the Space Shuttle Challenger disaster and the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:on-call-practices/shift-work] The Alaska Oil Spill Commission's final report on the *Exxon Valdez* oil spill disaster found that it was "conceivable" that excessive work hours contributed to crew fatigue, which in turn contributed to the vessel's running aground.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:on-call-practices/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
